  "slug": "pane-di-altamura",
  "title": "Pane di Altamura",
  "subtitle": "Pugliese durum semolina loaf",
  "excerpt": "The bread of Altamura in Puglia, made entirely with durum wheat semolina and shaped into the traditional U-shape or round. The golden crumb is dense and nutty, the crust thick and almost crackerlike, a loaf that improves on the second day.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Pane di Altamura has DOP (Protected Designation of Origin) status in Italy and must be made with durum wheat from the Murgia plateau to carry the name commercially. The method described here is based on traditional Pugliese home-baking practice documented in Italian regional food literature and agricultural extension material. Semolina rimacinata (twice-milled) is the domestic substitute for the traditional molino-ground flour.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Durum wheat makes a bread that nothing else quite replicates: a golden crumb, almost sandy in texture but cohesive, with a crust that is thick and hard and improves with keeping. "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Semolina rimacinata",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Semolina rimacinata",
                  "termId": "cmpbaq8pm0000pgv4d04kqfkd"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " is the flour to find: twice-milled durum, fine enough for bread but still coarser than plain flour. Coarse semolina (polenta-grind) does not work here; it absorbs water differently and gives a gritty crumb."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Ingredients"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "ingredientsList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "slug": "semolina-rimacinata",
              "unit": "g",
              "amount": 500,
              "prepNote": "semolina rimacinata (fine durum semolina)"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "slug": "water",
              "unit": "ml",
              "amount": 325,
              "prepNote": "lukewarm"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "slug": "dried-yeast",
              "unit": "g",
              "amount": 5
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "slug": "salt",
              "unit": "g",
              "amount": 10
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "ingredientItem",
            "attrs": {
              "slug": "olive-oil",
              "unit": "tbsp",
              "amount": 1
            }
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Method"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Autolyse, 30 minutes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Combine the semolina and 300 ml of the lukewarm water in a large bowl. Mix until no dry flour remains, then cover and rest for 30 minutes. This "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "autolyse",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                        "attrs": {
                          "term": "autolyse",
                          "termId": "cmp87mgal0001dcv47448winm"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " step lets the coarse grain hydrate fully and gives the gluten a head start, which matters with durum's tough protein network."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Add yeast, salt, and knead"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Dissolve the yeast in the remaining 25 ml of water. Add to the dough along with the salt and olive oil."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Knead by hand for 12 to 15 minutes until the dough is smooth and elastic. Durum dough is stiffer than plain-flour bread dough at the same hydration; it should feel firm but pliable, not sticky."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Bulk ferment, 2 hours"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Place in a lightly oiled bowl, cover, and leave at room temperature for 2 hours until doubled. Semolina dough ferments a little more slowly than white flour bread; give it the full time."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Shape and proof, 90 minutes"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Turn the dough onto an unfloured surface. Shape into a tight round, or the traditional U-shape (cappello di monaco): roll the dough into a long oval, fold one third over the centre, fold the other third over that, then curve the ends to form a crescent."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Place on a semolina-dusted baking sheet, cover, and proof for 90 minutes. The loaf should have clearly puffed when viewed from the side."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Score and bake"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "orderedList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Preheat the oven to 230°C conventional with a baking stone on the middle shelf and a water tray on the floor. The oven needs at least 45 minutes to reach a genuine 230°C; domestic ovens can drift by 20°C or more, so an oven thermometer is useful."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Score the top of the loaf with a sharp blade in a single long slash or a grid pattern."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Slide onto the hot stone and bake for 15 minutes with the water tray in place. Remove the tray and bake for a further 25 to 30 minutes until the crust is deep amber and sounds hollow when tapped. An internal probe reading of 96°C confirms it is done."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
